- Tue 14 May 2019 Ituri: Threatened with Ebola contamination, Mbororo farmers have left Mambasa to return to Haut-Uele
[Crofsblog, Bunia Actualite report, abridged, edited]
https://crofsblogs.typepad.com/h5n1/2019/05/ituri-threatened-with-ebola-contamination-mbororo-farmers-have-left-mambasa-to-return-to-haut-u%C3%A9l%C3%A9.html

The interim governor of Ituri announced the departure of approximately 3000 West African Mbororo pastoralists who had already settled in Mambasa territory, along with their cows, whose number is estimated by the local authorities, between 15 000 and 20 000. These nomads returned to the neighboring province of Haut-Uele [directly north of Ituri province] from which they had come.

"We have been in contact with the group leader and the Mambasa Territory Administrator who are confirming that the Mbororo have left our province. They found that the conditions were not favorable and that the environment was not conducive to their activities, "said Pacifique Keta in an interview on Mon 13 May 2019 to our fellow radio Okapi.

Among the major causes of their departure, the provincial authority cites in particular their fear of being infected by the Ebola virus epidemic, as well as the payment of a provincial tax on the movement of livestock imposed on them.

"Some of their cows died, they realized that this was already a bad sign. They feared a possible contamination by Ebola," he continued.

The Mbororo are a West African nomadic pastoral people, and not always welcome among more settled communities.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

- Fri 17 May 2019. Video: David Miliband, Eyewitness to the fight against Ebola
[IRC (International Rescue Committee), abridged, edited]
https://www.rescue.org/video/david-miliband-eyewitness-fight-against-ebola

International Rescue Committee president and CEO David Miliband recently visited the IRC's Ebola response in the Democratic Republic of Congo. Congo has spent decades in the grip of violent conflict, and attacks on health centers are hindering efforts to treat patients and prevent the spread of the virus.

Video transcript
----------------
I'm convinced that the Ebola crisis taking place north of here in the cities of Beni and Butembo is far more worrying, far more dangerous than is generally realized.

David Miliband recently visited IRC's Ebola response in Goma, Democratic Republic of Congo.

IRC staff are supporting over 50 health centers to tackle Ebola.

The places where Ebola seems to be out of the grip of authorities are conflict zones.

Attacks on health centers have halted many Ebola treatment and prevention programs.

Here in Goma, people are worried that Ebola is going to arrive, it's going to be brought here.

With Ebola cases rising, the outbreak is far from under control.

It's very, very important that the government, the international community press the reset button, step up together, to change the approach, to win the confidence of the local community to make sure that the coordination of the effort is of the highest order.

--
